<br>
When I saw the movie I thought the point of the nudity was to emphasize the mind/body or ghost/shell division.  The whole theme of the movie (at least in my opinion) was that this new technology has made it possible to seperate the two, as in the case of Motoko whose body is completely new, or the Puppet master who was created without a body.  By having Motoko nude, or at least extremely exposed, I thought the idea was to really make it obvious that they were talking about the body in an abstract, philosophical sense.  I mean if you want to say that your body is just a shell for your mind/soul but is completely unattached to it, it makes sense to use nudity.  Its almost a statement about human nature or about the physical world and the metaphysical world -- clothing just doesn't enter into the equation.<br>
<br>
